Reference-contexts: An HFC network can provide the bandwidth that some multimedia applications require, using the spectrum from 5 MHz to 450 MHz for conventional downstream analog information, and the spectrum from 450 MHz to 750 MHz for digital broadcast services such as voice and video telephony, video-on-demand, and interactive television <ref> [2] </ref>. 3 2 HFC The basic fiber-coax network is already taking shape, driven by the video entertainment delivery business [3]. <p> For analog distribution, the headend includes transmission equipment such as frequency modulators and combiners, and for digital distribution, high speed ATM switches. A SONET ring connects the switches in the headend to distribution centers and to the rest of the access network <ref> [2] </ref>. Distribution centers are responsible for routing information from the headend to the subscribers' homes. Multiple services (voice telephony, digital video, and data services) are delivered to subscribers' homes by employing different modulation schemes and FDM techniques. <p> Distribution centers also controls the spectrum allocation, or the allocation for frequency bands for different services for the neighborhood it serves. Since HFC is a point-to-multipoint transmission network, the subscriber may request encryption to protect sensitive data. The distribution 6 center controls and manages encryption services <ref> [2] </ref>. Fiber nodes serving clusters of 500 to 2000 homes receive their signal feed from regional distribution centers. <p> The coaxial lines carry the signal a short distance to the subscriber, with amplifiers at appropriate places to prevent attenuation <ref> [2] </ref>. At the subscribers' homes, a variety of devices may be used to access information transmitted over the HFC network (see Figure 2). Voice telephony, video access, and data services are a few of the services that can be extracted from the network interface unit [2]. 2.3 Spectrum Allocation assumes a <p> appropriate